Intuition
At every node we have two possible ways for the trees to be flip equivalent,

without fliiping at current node
left subtreee should match left subtree , and right subtree should match right subtree
with flipping the current node, left subtree should match right subtree and right subtree should match left subtree
if either of these possibilities is valid , then the current pair of node is flip equivalent.

efore exploring these possibilities, we handle the base cases:

If both nodes are None, they are equivalent.
If only one node is None, they cannot be equivalent.
If the node values differ, no amount of flipping can make them equal.

Complexity
⏱️ Time Complexity

Let n be the number of nodes in the smaller tree.

Each recursive call compares a pair of nodes.
In the worst case, both the without flip and with flip possibilities are explored at many nodes.
This can lead to revisiting different subtree pairings, giving a worst-case time complexity of O(n²).

Time Complexity: O(n²) (worst case)

📦 Space Complexity

The extra space comes from the recursion stack.

In the worst case (a skewed tree), the recursion depth is equal to the height of the tree.

Space Complexity: O(h)

Worst case: O(n) (skewed tree)
Balanced tree: O(log n)

Code
# Definition for a binary tree node.
# class TreeNode:
#     def __init__(self, val=0, left=None, right=None):
#         self.val = val
#         self.left = left
#         self.right = right
class Solution:
    def flipEquiv(self, root1: Optional[TreeNode], root2: Optional[TreeNode]) -> bool:
        def dfs(node1,node2):
            if node1 is None and node2 is None: return True
            if node1 is None or node2 is None: return False
            if node1.val != node2.val: return False
            without_flip = dfs(node1.left,node2.left) and dfs(node1.right,node2.right)
            flip = dfs(node1.left, node2.right) and dfs(node1.right , node2.left)
            return without_flip  or flip
        return dfs(root1,root2)
     
